1
00:00:00,320 --> 00:00:05,440
Here’s a situation you’ll probably relate to.
You sit in front of your screen. 

2
00:00:05,440 --> 00:00:10,760
You watch a trade inch closer to your stop-loss.
Your heart beats faster. 

3
00:00:10,760 --> 00:00:16,080
You feel that twist in your stomach.
It grows stronger as the price dips  

4
00:00:16,080 --> 00:00:19,120
against your position.
You tell yourself that you  

5
00:00:19,120 --> 00:00:22,800
must act….but you hesitate!
You wonder if you should  

6
00:00:22,800 --> 00:00:28,240
close your trade early or wait.
Hundreds of thoughts spin in your head. 

7
00:00:28,240 --> 00:00:31,560
Then you see the market 
push more against you again. 

8
00:00:31,560 --> 00:00:37,400
You then click to exit with trembling 
fingers, and the loss hits your account. 

9
00:00:37,400 --> 00:00:43,760
You then feel a wave of regret, and even shame.
And then you begin to blame yourself! 

10
00:00:43,760 --> 00:00:50,280
Every trader knows this feeling all too well!
This moment captures one major burden:  

11
00:00:50,280 --> 00:00:54,920
the fear of losing.
You worry about your capital vanishing. 

12
00:00:54,920 --> 00:00:58,600
You might dread blowing up your account.
You might keep your trade  

13
00:00:58,600 --> 00:01:04,520
open out of stubborn hope.
Or you might rush to exit too soon from panic. 

14
00:01:04,520 --> 00:01:08,840
That fear can turn you inside out.
It can freeze your mind. 

15
00:01:08,840 --> 00:01:13,840
You might stare at the chart, hoping 
it will turn in your favor, yet you do  

16
00:01:13,840 --> 00:01:17,680
nothing at the right time.
This fear steals your  

17
00:01:17,680 --> 00:01:24,240
clarity. It blinds you to good choices.
It pulls you away from your trading plan. 

18
00:01:24,240 --> 00:01:29,680
It makes you question your skill and your worth.
You see, loss is scary. 

19
00:01:29,680 --> 00:01:34,680
When you see a big red number in your 
account, you might lash out at the market. 

20
00:01:34,680 --> 00:01:38,440
You might get angry, or you 
might make reckless moves. 

21
00:01:38,440 --> 00:01:43,560
Revenge trading can happen with such 
anger. You try to hunt for a quick fix. 

22
00:01:43,560 --> 00:01:50,920
You slam into the market again with full position 
size, hoping the next trade wipes out the loss. 

23
00:01:50,920 --> 00:01:56,280
But this rarely works! And your 
initial loss…well, it just doubled!

24
00:01:56,280 --> 00:02:02,680
Greed is another item in this puzzle. You 
see a new hot stock or a new cryptocurrency. 

25
00:02:02,680 --> 00:02:06,400
Or you see a setup that 
looks like an easy jackpot. 

26
00:02:06,400 --> 00:02:12,800
And you enter, hoping for a quick gain. If 
it goes right, you might celebrate too soon. 

27
00:02:12,800 --> 00:02:18,760
You might become overconfident. If it 
goes wrong, you might chase more trades. 

28
00:02:18,760 --> 00:02:24,880
You try to get that same excitement back. This 
dangerous hunger often leads to overtrading. 

29
00:02:24,880 --> 00:02:31,680
You hop into the market with random entries. 
You break your rules. You ignore your risk. 

30
00:02:31,680 --> 00:02:35,400
You guess blindly and hope to find gold. 

31
00:02:35,400 --> 00:02:41,000
And at the end of the day, when you look at 
your account, you see red, and lots of it.

32
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:46,280
Boredom can strike too. You sit for 
hours. You watch the prices crawl. 

33
00:02:46,280 --> 00:02:50,720
You want action. You decide 
to take a trade with no plan. 

34
00:02:50,720 --> 00:02:54,600
That boredom-driven trade often spells trouble. 

35
00:02:54,600 --> 00:02:59,840
The market does not care that you are bored.
The market is busy living its own life. 

36
00:03:00,520 --> 00:03:06,280
This leads to slippage in your discipline. 
It leads to trades you cannot explain. 

37
00:03:06,280 --> 00:03:09,960
Then you wonder why you clicked 
the button in the first place. 

38
00:03:09,960 --> 00:03:14,160
You ask yourself if you can 
even follow a simple plan!

39
00:03:14,160 --> 00:03:20,200
Many also struggle with “analysis paralysis.”
You stare at your charts. You flip through  

40
00:03:20,200 --> 00:03:25,040
indicators. You read one more tweet.
You watch one more video.  

41
00:03:25,040 --> 00:03:29,480
You second-guess your plan.
Should you wait for a pullback? Should you switch  

42
00:03:29,480 --> 00:03:35,720
time frames? Should you tweak your settings?
Your mind becomes a storm of “what ifs!” 

43
00:03:35,720 --> 00:03:40,320
And you watch your setup pass.
Price moves in the way you predicted,  

44
00:03:40,320 --> 00:03:47,720
but you did nothing. You feel frustration.
You feel that you missed a big gain. Next time,  

45
00:03:47,720 --> 00:03:53,240
you promise yourself not to overthink.
Then you do the same cycle again!

46
00:03:53,240 --> 00:03:59,720
Some traders face unrealistic expectations. They 
think they can double their account each week. 

47
00:04:00,240 --> 00:04:06,400
They dream of perfect trades with no risk. They 
think they can live on an island next year. 

48
00:04:06,400 --> 00:04:10,000
They see social media gurus brag about new cars. 

49
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:17,560
So they put on giant trades to chase giant wins.
And their account blows when reality sets in.

50
00:04:17,560 --> 00:04:22,200
Pressure is also constant. You might 
see your friends posting gains. 

51
00:04:22,200 --> 00:04:26,240
You might hear someone boasting 
about a big Bitcoin run. 

52
00:04:26,240 --> 00:04:32,120
And you want to keep up. You fear missing 
out. And you jump in at the worst time. 

53
00:04:32,120 --> 00:04:37,680
Then price dips. And you feel foolish. 
You might try to buy dips again. 

54
00:04:37,680 --> 00:04:44,240
If it keeps dipping, you panic even more.
Then you regret not waiting for a clear signal. 

55
00:04:44,240 --> 00:04:49,320
Your mind flicks between fear of 
missing out and fear of losing. 

56
00:04:49,320 --> 00:04:53,480
That internal conflict 
leads to emotional whiplash.

57
00:04:53,480 --> 00:04:59,280
All these struggles hurt your confidence. You 
think trading is all about charts, but you see  

58
00:04:59,280 --> 00:05:04,680
that your mind can sabotage each decision.
You see that you are dealing with your  

59
00:05:04,680 --> 00:05:08,920
own emotions as much as you 
are dealing with the market. 

60
00:05:08,920 --> 00:05:17,440
This reveals the truth: trading is a mental game.
Charts, indicators, and systems matter. But your  

61
00:05:17,440 --> 00:05:22,360
mindset decides how you use them.
If your mind is locked in fear,  

62
00:05:22,360 --> 00:05:28,720
or stuck in greed, or swayed by anger, 
you cannot follow even the best plan. 

63
00:05:28,720 --> 00:05:33,280
It all starts with your psychology.
The invisible battles you face each  

64
00:05:33,280 --> 00:05:39,720
day are shared by all of us who trade.
Each fear, each mistake, each wave of  

65
00:05:39,720 --> 00:05:44,160
guilt is part of the common trader’s story. 
 
What Traders Do Wrong: The Root Causes of Failure

66
00:05:44,160 --> 00:05:50,440
Traders often ignore their own plans.
Initially, they craft a step-by-step system. 

67
00:05:50,440 --> 00:05:56,360
They detail entries, exits, and risk levels.
Yet, in the heat of the moment,  

68
00:05:56,360 --> 00:06:01,840
they throw it all out.
They see a quick jump in price. They chase it. 

69
00:06:01,840 --> 00:06:06,120
Then, they see a large drop. 
And they exit in a panic. 

70
00:06:06,120 --> 00:06:10,880
Their trades become impulsive.
And this leads to confusion.  

71
00:06:10,880 --> 00:06:17,200
It leads to random results.
Your plan is just a piece of paper, with no use.

72
00:06:17,200 --> 00:06:23,280
You might obsess over a single trade’s gain 
or loss. You might celebrate a fast gain. 

73
00:06:23,280 --> 00:06:29,200
Or you might dwell on a sad loss.
You measure your worth on that one outcome. 

74
00:06:29,200 --> 00:06:35,360
Then your next trade falls into the same trap.
You react to the last result instead of  

75
00:06:35,360 --> 00:06:39,600
thinking of the long-term path.
But you see, even a person with  

76
00:06:39,600 --> 00:06:44,560
a strong system can fail, if they 
get stuck in short-term thinking. 

77
00:06:44,560 --> 00:06:48,120
At the beginning of the day 
you knew you had a plan. 

78
00:06:48,120 --> 00:06:52,640
Yet you let a single good or bad result shake you!

79
00:06:52,640 --> 00:07:00,400
Emotional trading is widespread. Fear, greed, 
frustration, envy—these circle within you. 

80
00:07:00,400 --> 00:07:07,200
You might have a plan that says to risk 3%.
Then you panic and risk 20% because  

81
00:07:07,200 --> 00:07:11,880
you “feel” it is a sure bet.
Or you might bail on a winning trade  

82
00:07:11,880 --> 00:07:18,960
too soon because your heart pounds with fear.
You see, emotions can override logic! 

83
00:07:18,960 --> 00:07:24,520
This type of trading sets you up for 
chaos. It erodes your discipline!

84
00:07:24,520 --> 00:07:29,520
Chasing losses is another pattern. 
You might take a trade and lose. 

85
00:07:29,520 --> 00:07:33,280
You feel a sting of shame.
You want your money back. So  

86
00:07:33,280 --> 00:07:37,680
you jump in without a plan, 
hoping to recoup your loss. 

87
00:07:37,680 --> 00:07:43,280
That trade might fail too. Now you feel 
even worse. You doubled your losses. 

88
00:07:43,280 --> 00:07:48,520
And you keep throwing money at bad setups.
At the end of the day, you wonder  

89
00:07:48,520 --> 00:07:54,120
how you ended so deep in losses.
And you blame the market or your luck. 

90
00:07:54,120 --> 00:07:59,440
But the truth is your choice, fueled 
by anger and desperation, led to that!

91
00:08:00,200 --> 00:08:05,600
Overconfidence can arise after a streak 
of wins. You might feel invincible. 

92
00:08:05,600 --> 00:08:11,040
You might think each setup will be a 
winner. You might raise your size too fast. 

93
00:08:11,040 --> 00:08:16,440
You might skip risk measures.
Then the market humbles you! One large  

94
00:08:16,440 --> 00:08:20,760
loss wipes out all your gains.
And you feel shocked.  

95
00:08:20,760 --> 00:08:26,640
You wonder where your luck went.
Then you blame the market gods for punishing you. 

96
00:08:26,640 --> 00:08:31,280
But once again, you ignored your 
plan. You took on too much risk. 

97
00:08:31,280 --> 00:08:37,280
You forgot that losses can come at any 
time. That is the root of the problem!

98
00:08:37,280 --> 00:08:41,800
Confirmation bias leads you to 
filter the information you see. 

99
00:08:41,800 --> 00:08:48,280
You might want to go long a stock. You read 
only bullish news. You skip the warnings. 

100
00:08:48,280 --> 00:08:53,240
You only see charts that confirm your view.
If you find any bearish sign,  

101
00:08:53,240 --> 00:08:59,560
you dismiss it. Then the stock tanks.
You are caught off guard. And you feel tricked. 

102
00:08:59,560 --> 00:09:03,760
Yet you tricked yourself. You 
closed your eyes to other angles. 

103
00:09:03,760 --> 00:09:08,000
You chose to see only what matched your bias.

104
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:15,520
Traders also fall for the sunk cost fallacy. You 
analyze a setup for a whole day, and you enter. 

105
00:09:15,520 --> 00:09:18,800
But it goes south right after you enter. 

106
00:09:18,800 --> 00:09:23,160
You think, “I’ve spent so much 
time on this. I have to wait!” 

107
00:09:23,160 --> 00:09:28,920
And you hold, ignoring your stop-loss, 
because you feel you are too invested. 

108
00:09:28,920 --> 00:09:34,440
You cannot stand to accept a loss. You 
might even add to the losing position. 

109
00:09:34,440 --> 00:09:40,760
You hope it will return to your entry.
You linger on that bad trade far too long. 

110
00:09:40,760 --> 00:09:45,800
The problem is you don’t want to admit 
the trade was flawed from the start.

111
00:09:45,800 --> 00:09:50,360
These behaviors create a loop 
of poor results and stress. 

112
00:09:50,360 --> 00:09:55,840
You keep falling into the same traps: 
ignoring your plan, letting emotions rule,  

113
00:09:55,840 --> 00:10:00,920
chasing after losses, or riding 
that wave of overconfidence. 

114
00:10:00,920 --> 00:10:07,360
You make the same mistakes over and over.
Awareness is the first step. All  

115
00:10:07,360 --> 00:10:12,600
these actions come from within you.
Once you see them, you can address them. 

116
00:10:12,600 --> 00:10:16,440
You cannot blame the market. 
The market simply moves. 

117
00:10:16,440 --> 00:10:19,560
Your job is to control you! 
 
Dopamine, Stress, and Decision-Making

118
00:10:19,560 --> 00:10:26,360
Traders often get hooked by the promise of profit.
That excitement triggers dopamine in the brain. 

119
00:10:26,360 --> 00:10:30,840
Dopamine is a chemical that 
influences reward-seeking actions. 

120
00:10:30,840 --> 00:10:36,560
It is the same chemical that can lead a 
gambler to keep pulling the slot machine lever. 

121
00:10:36,560 --> 00:10:42,640
You see a potential big win, and your brain 
lights up. You feel a rush of anticipation. 

122
00:10:42,640 --> 00:10:45,800
But this rush can override reason. 

123
00:10:45,800 --> 00:10:50,000
You know the feeling: you see 
a setup and imagine fast gains. 

124
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:54,600
You might ignore your risk rules. 
You might jump in with no caution. 

125
00:10:54,600 --> 00:10:59,240
Your mind wants that thrill! This pattern 
can repeat itself like an addiction. 

126
00:11:00,120 --> 00:11:04,240
Each time you open a new trade, 
you get a jolt of possibility. 

127
00:11:04,240 --> 00:11:08,680
You crave that rush again.
But this can spawn overtrading. 

128
00:11:08,680 --> 00:11:12,600
You chase setups that are 
not aligned with your plan.

129
00:11:12,600 --> 00:11:19,800
Stress also plays a major role. When a trade 
goes against you, your body can release cortisol. 

130
00:11:19,800 --> 00:11:23,440
That stress hormone primes 
you for fight or flight. 

131
00:11:23,440 --> 00:11:29,320
That works well in physical danger, but 
in trading, it can cloud your judgment. 

132
00:11:29,320 --> 00:11:35,600
Your hands might sweat. Your heart might race. 
Your mind might fixate on the potential loss. 

133
00:11:35,600 --> 00:11:41,200
You might exit a good trade too soon out 
of panic. Or you might revenge trade. 

134
00:11:41,200 --> 00:11:47,400
You are just reacting to stress signals in 
your body. That reaction is not rational.

135
00:11:47,400 --> 00:11:53,560
Over time, you can get mentally tired. 
Watching charts for hours is draining. 

136
00:11:53,560 --> 00:11:58,720
Making many decisions is also 
draining. Decision fatigue sets in. 

137
00:11:58,720 --> 00:12:04,440
The more you force yourself to focus without 
pause, the weaker your willpower becomes. 

138
00:12:04,440 --> 00:12:11,080
You might make silly errors. You might 
misread a chart or place the wrong order size.

139
00:12:11,080 --> 00:12:15,720
Knowing these bodily and mental 
processes can help you pause. 

140
00:12:15,720 --> 00:12:20,000
You can feel when it is 
dopamine or stress driving you. 

141
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:24,000
One helpful approach is journaling.
This is a way to bring  

142
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:29,480
conscious thought to your actions.
You note what you felt before you took a trade. 

143
00:12:29,480 --> 00:12:35,120
You notice if you felt an urge for a 
quick high. You notice if you felt fear. 

144
00:12:35,120 --> 00:12:39,160
Writing it down makes it real.
Then you can reflect. 

145
00:12:39,160 --> 00:12:43,480
Over time, you see patterns of 
behavior. You see exactly which  

146
00:12:43,480 --> 00:12:50,040
trades were fueled by an emotional rush. 
You see which trades were calm and planned.

147
00:12:50,040 --> 00:12:55,280
Trust me, tracking your mood will help. 
It’s like keeping an emotional log. 

148
00:12:55,280 --> 00:13:01,720
You rate your anxiety or excitement levels at 
certain times and you note it in a journal. 

149
00:13:01,720 --> 00:13:05,760
This might feel odd, but it 
highlights hidden patterns. 

150
00:13:05,760 --> 00:13:11,240
Maybe you are always extra impulsive 
after a few hours waiting for a signal. 

151
00:13:11,240 --> 00:13:15,200
Maybe you are anxious when 
you’re trade doesn’t move much. 

152
00:13:15,200 --> 00:13:21,960
By noting these patterns, you can avoid big 
trades when you are prone to tilt or frustration.

153
00:13:21,960 --> 00:13:28,440
Remember this: when you trade, you want to 
break the dopamine highs and the cortisol lows. 

154
00:13:28,440 --> 00:13:33,051
You need to bring your trading 
back to a levelheaded space. 
 
 

155
00:13:33,051 --> 00:13:35,280
Building Emotional Resilience
Now let’s talk about resilience! 

156
00:13:35,280 --> 00:13:40,640
Resilience means you bounce back after 
a loss. You do not stay in despair. 

157
00:13:40,640 --> 00:13:46,200
You do not let it ruin your whole week. 
You accept that losing trades happen. 

158
00:13:46,200 --> 00:13:49,960
You focus on the next step.
You also do not become too  

159
00:13:49,960 --> 00:13:56,400
arrogant after a win. You stay steady.
You speak to yourself with calm assurance. 

160
00:13:56,400 --> 00:14:02,680
I know, easier said than done…
Unfortunately, resilience is built with practice. 

161
00:14:02,680 --> 00:14:07,640
Each time you push through a tough day, 
you are training your emotional muscle. 

162
00:14:07,640 --> 00:14:15,240
One tool for resilience is acceptance. If you 
deny losses or blame the market, you do not grow. 

163
00:14:15,240 --> 00:14:21,440
If you accept that losses are part of trading, 
you free yourself from shock when they arrive. 

164
00:14:21,440 --> 00:14:27,040
You plan for them with risk controls.
You do not tie your ego to each trade. 

165
00:14:27,040 --> 00:14:31,760
You see it as a probability game.
The focus is on the long run. 

166
00:14:31,760 --> 00:14:36,240
This acceptance helps you 
handle each outcome with grace.

167
00:14:36,240 --> 00:14:40,600
Another tool is self-awareness. 
You need to know your triggers. 

168
00:14:40,600 --> 00:14:44,720
Some traders get overly excited 
after two wins in a row. 

169
00:14:44,720 --> 00:14:51,600
Some get crippled by fear after a single big loss.
Some freeze when they need to pull the trigger. 

170
00:14:51,600 --> 00:14:55,800
By studying your emotions, 
you identify these triggers. 

171
00:14:55,800 --> 00:14:59,320
Then you can plan.
You can decide not to trade after two  

172
00:14:59,320 --> 00:15:07,160
wins if you sense overconfidence is creeping in.
Or you can reduce size after a large loss.

173
00:15:07,160 --> 00:15:12,000
Consistency in size and process 
also fosters resilience. 

174
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:16,040
If you keep your position size 
consistent, you avoid emotional  

175
00:15:16,040 --> 00:15:21,600
spikes tied to random big positions.
If you keep a checklist for each trade,  

176
00:15:21,600 --> 00:15:27,720
you can measure your actions against that list.
When you follow the list, you feel stable because  

177
00:15:27,720 --> 00:15:31,080
you know you are sticking 
to a disciplined approach. 

178
00:15:31,080 --> 00:15:36,400
If you skip it, you see why you got off 
track. You can correct it next time.

179
00:15:36,400 --> 00:15:43,160
Resilience grows when you see setbacks as lessons.
Each loss can teach something. Maybe you  

180
00:15:43,160 --> 00:15:48,920
learned the market was in a different mode.
Maybe you learned you were in an anxious state. 

181
00:15:48,920 --> 00:15:52,960
Maybe you learned your stop was too tight.
Maybe you were fooled by a  

182
00:15:52,960 --> 00:15:58,120
candle or a quick price spike.
Instead of letting it crush your spirit,  

183
00:15:58,120 --> 00:16:00,600
you update your plan!
 
Mastering Discipline

184
00:16:00,600 --> 00:16:05,400
Discipline is more than ticking off 
boxes. It is following a structure,  

185
00:16:05,400 --> 00:16:10,120
even when emotions scream at you.
You might have a plan that says:  

186
00:16:10,120 --> 00:16:19,000
“I trade only at certain times. I only risk 
2% per trade. I exit at a specific signal.” 

187
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:23,960
Then a big news event spikes the price.
Friends on social media are  

188
00:16:23,960 --> 00:16:28,920
cheering about easy gains.
And you feel the urge to jump in. 

189
00:16:28,920 --> 00:16:32,480
Discipline is what stops 
you from ignoring your plan. 

190
00:16:32,480 --> 00:16:39,800
That’s why, you must always consult your rules. 
If it is not in your plan, you stand aside.

191
00:16:39,800 --> 00:16:44,480
Traders sometimes see discipline 
as boring. They want excitement. 

192
00:16:44,480 --> 00:16:50,160
They want the thrill of big moves. But 
that thrill can lead to reckless decisions. 

193
00:16:50,160 --> 00:16:54,920
The best traders often repeat 
the same type of trade for years. 

194
00:16:54,920 --> 00:17:00,840
They are calm about their routine. They 
do not chase random markets or trades. 

195
00:17:00,840 --> 00:17:05,560
They stick to what they know. Their 
discipline keeps them out of trouble. 

196
00:17:05,560 --> 00:17:09,200
It might not be flashy. But it is steady.

197
00:17:09,200 --> 00:17:13,640
Self-discipline can erode if 
you let small exceptions slide. 

198
00:17:13,640 --> 00:17:19,320
You might say, “I will just increase 
size a bit today. It is a sure setup.” 

199
00:17:19,320 --> 00:17:24,400
Or “I will hold this loss 
beyond my stop, just this once.” 

200
00:17:24,400 --> 00:17:28,480
Each time you do that, you 
chip away at your discipline. 

201
00:17:28,480 --> 00:17:34,680
You teach your mind that the rules are flexible.
Then a bigger slip happens next time. 

202
00:17:34,680 --> 00:17:40,560
Soon you have no clear anchor.
And I guarantee, you will blow your account!

203
00:17:40,560 --> 00:17:46,560
Routine is a powerful ally. If you have a 
pre-trade checklist, follow it each day. 

204
00:17:46,560 --> 00:17:52,880
Check the market conditions. Check your 
entry, your potential exit, your technicals. 

205
00:17:52,880 --> 00:17:58,120
Check your risk and your mindset.
After your session, review the trades.  

206
00:17:58,120 --> 00:18:04,800
Write brief notes. That pattern keeps you 
grounded and prevents emotional leaps.

207
00:18:04,800 --> 00:18:09,760
Sometimes, no trading is the best trading.
Some days, you might notice  

208
00:18:09,760 --> 00:18:13,120
your mind is distracted.
Or you might see that the market  

209
00:18:13,120 --> 00:18:19,240
is choppy and does not match your setup.
Not trading is also a decision.  

210
00:18:19,240 --> 00:18:23,080
It keeps your account safe.
You see, many traders think they  

211
00:18:23,080 --> 00:18:26,960
must be in the market always.
They fear missing out. 

212
00:18:26,960 --> 00:18:32,080
A disciplined trader just waits for the 
conditions that match their strategy. 

213
00:18:32,080 --> 00:18:36,778
That is how they protect themselves 
and preserve their capital. 
  

214
00:18:36,778 --> 00:18:36,840
Trading Your Own Path: Avoiding 
Comparisons and External Noise

215
00:18:36,840 --> 00:18:41,760
Some traders keep scanning social 
media. They see big wins posted. 

216
00:18:41,760 --> 00:18:44,400
They see markets that went up a lot. 

217
00:18:44,400 --> 00:18:47,520
They beat themselves up 
for not catching that move. 

218
00:18:47,520 --> 00:18:53,440
They chase hot tips from random influencers.
This leads to confusion. It leads  

219
00:18:53,440 --> 00:18:59,960
to trades with no personal reason.
And soon, it will lead to fear and regret. 

220
00:18:59,960 --> 00:19:04,520
Comparison can turn a stable 
trader into a frantic mess. 

221
00:19:04,520 --> 00:19:10,240
Objects in your feed might not be real 
either. Many people only show their wins. 

222
00:19:10,240 --> 00:19:16,520
They might hide big losses. Chasing 
illusions can harm you more than you know.

223
00:19:16,520 --> 00:19:21,920
Some people rely too much on gurus. 
They copy trades they see on a stream. 

224
00:19:21,920 --> 00:19:27,760
They never learn to form their own plan.
They do not have a strong foundation themselves. 

225
00:19:27,760 --> 00:19:33,200
Blind following leads to confusion. 
It also prevents real growth. 

226
00:19:33,200 --> 00:19:38,920
You need YOUR own tested strategy.
That might incorporate tips from others,  

227
00:19:38,920 --> 00:19:42,480
but YOU must adapt them to fit your style.

228
00:19:42,480 --> 00:19:47,240
You must also define your “why.”
Why do you trade? Is it for a secure  

229
00:19:47,240 --> 00:19:51,680
future? Is it for the thrill?
Is it to test yourself? Get  

230
00:19:51,680 --> 00:19:57,440
that reason clear. Write it down.
That reason becomes your anchor.

231
00:19:57,440 --> 00:20:02,080
Shifting your mind from “winning” 
to “improving” will help you. 

232
00:20:02,080 --> 00:20:09,000
You stop chasing big payouts for show. And 
you start focusing on consistent execution. 

233
00:20:09,000 --> 00:20:12,880
You might measure your day by 
how well you followed your plan. 

234
00:20:12,880 --> 00:20:19,800
If you followed it 100%, that is a win!
Even if the trade ended in a small loss,  

235
00:20:19,800 --> 00:20:25,240
you are building skill.
Over time, that skill leads to profits.

236
00:20:25,240 --> 00:20:31,080
So limit external distractions. Stay 
off social media during trading sessions  

237
00:20:31,080 --> 00:20:38,640
if it tempts you to make random decisions.
If certain forums spark envy or panic, block them. 

238
00:20:38,640 --> 00:20:43,040
Seek only solid, balanced 
resources that match your style. 

239
00:20:43,040 --> 00:20:49,120
It is better to have focused, in-depth 
practice than to jump at every new idea. 

240
00:20:49,120 --> 00:20:53,960
If you see something that might help, 
test it in a demo or small account. 

241
00:20:53,960 --> 00:20:56,720
See if it works with your plan.
 
 
Reflection and Continuous Improvement

242
00:20:56,720 --> 00:21:02,080
Some traders overcomplicate their 
strategies. They change indicators daily. 

243
00:21:02,080 --> 00:21:08,720
They tweak settings each time a trade fails.
Others suffer from procrastination. Instead  

244
00:21:08,720 --> 00:21:14,160
of placing trades, they spend hours 
adjusting lines on their charts. 

245
00:21:14,160 --> 00:21:19,200
They might fear real outcomes, so 
they stay in a loop of refining. 

246
00:21:19,200 --> 00:21:23,160
They never have to face the 
risk of real commitment. 

247
00:21:23,160 --> 00:21:28,840
Recognizing these patterns is the first step.
You might notice you always close a trade  

248
00:21:28,840 --> 00:21:34,920
early when it starts to get profitable.
You might see that you disregard your rules when  

249
00:21:34,920 --> 00:21:42,560
you are close to a big milestone in your account.
Many times, this self-sabotage stems from the  

250
00:21:42,560 --> 00:21:45,920
desire for perfection.
I said it before,  

251
00:21:45,920 --> 00:21:51,920
a trading journal is your best friend here.
It is a place to record not just your entry  

252
00:21:51,920 --> 00:21:57,760
and exit, but your thoughts and emotions.
You write what you felt before you entered.  

253
00:21:57,760 --> 00:22:01,280
You note any hesitation.
You log your mood,  

254
00:22:01,280 --> 00:22:07,920
your confidence level, your reason for the trade.
Then you note what happened during and after the  

255
00:22:07,920 --> 00:22:14,880
trade. You might discover that each time you are 
feeling too excited, you tend to over-leverage. 

256
00:22:14,880 --> 00:22:20,480
Or when you are anxious, you exit too soon.
By reviewing the journal, you see  

257
00:22:20,480 --> 00:22:24,760
patterns in your decisions.
You spot which behaviors led  

258
00:22:24,760 --> 00:22:30,880
to consistent gains and which led to losses.
You might find that you do better in certain  

259
00:22:30,880 --> 00:22:35,480
market conditions or times of day.
You might find that you fall for  

260
00:22:35,480 --> 00:22:42,240
revenge trading after two losses in a row.
This awareness helps you create solutions.

261
00:22:42,240 --> 00:22:47,320
An open mind is vital. You might 
outgrow your strategy at some point. 

262
00:22:47,320 --> 00:22:51,480
The market might change and 
will strategy will stop working. 

263
00:22:51,480 --> 00:22:57,920
So keep an open mind and always try to 
learn new concepts, but do so with a filter. 

264
00:22:57,920 --> 00:23:02,080
Test new ideas in a small or demo account first. 

265
00:23:02,080 --> 00:23:07,520
If something seems to help, 
integrate it. If not, discard it! 

266
00:23:07,520 --> 00:23:14,560
Please always remember this: a strong mental 
game is better than having a strong strategy. 

267
00:23:14,560 --> 00:23:21,400
A trader with a strong mental game will always 
do better than one with a good strategy. 

268
00:23:21,400 --> 00:23:28,440
Now, if you want to keep improving your trading 
game, go ahead and watch one of these videos!

